Sydney Zink my bad! it's 336. I made an edit.
I've been told 336 is interesting but very hard, Hartline is probably the best prof. for it though.

321 is one of the most intellectually challenging classes and is a phenomenal class in every way. Highly recommend. 336 is almost a mandatory class to take, also very challenging but not the most interesting/fun class to take ( although I mainly say that because no programming is involved). 325 is all programming and it's got a very unique structure - no exams, no hw, no deadlines - just an infinite number of assignments you can master, and the more you complete, the higher are the chances of getting a good grade.
Anuj Iravane the reputation for the professor of 325 (Christopher Riesbeck) is not so great though. Do you still recommend it?

Careful, haha, I wouldn't say "reputation" is the right word to use here. I don't know what the CTEC's say about him but I think Prof.Riesbeck teaches that class really well. 
325 is all about solving fairly complex and interesting problems using minimal and optimal code. It uses Lisp (functional programming) which throws a lot of people off, because they believe its not the most popular skill to have (which is a misconception).
Anyway, if you're into functional programming or like to solve semantically complex but algorithmically simple problems for fun then you should definitely take it.
Whatever you do, don't graduate without 336. Algorithmic basis isn't superb at NU, and 336 is your best shot in that area of CS.

325 will make you a better programmer in general, since Riesbeck expects code to be well written and structured, not just functional. You submit and resubmit assignments online until they're done, so loss of points. The most important thing is to NOT PROCRASTINATE. If you do, you will have a bad time.
Lenny Hyungsuk Kim If that's the case, things have changed in the two years since I was there. I loved Riesbeck, and I wasn't aware of him having a negative reputation?
321 is awesome

Riesbeck was brutally stringent when it came to code review, but there are very few professors at NU I respected and appreciated as much as him. It's only been a few years and I've forgotten most of their names. Riesbeck may make you resubmit the same working code a dozen times if it is not immaculate and that can be really frustrating, but ultimately you will be far better off having been taught by him. Sinan (or anyone else) what do you recommend to learn Angular? Codeacademy just released a new AngularJS course, but I didn't really think it was too good. Books or online tutorials maybe?

Avy, that's a great question, and I have no idea what the answer is. 

TL;DR: (1) Read as much documentation as you can, (2) look at other people's code, (3) build your own projects and get/give help via StackOverflow as much as possible, (4) USE FIREBASE, (5) books and online courses suck.

I kept trying to learn Angular using books and "courses" but always felt like I was struggling and didn't feel like I ever got the "full picture". I think the books approach makes it hard to learn efficiently because books present pieces of AngularJS in a segmented way. I'd say that trying to learn from a book is pointless. I got the book "Pro AngularJS" but half the time, the author is just blabbering as if he's writing a fiction novel. The online courses were even worse because I got very impatient trying to follow examples that I didn't care about. 

I'd have to say that I learn best when building my own projects, constantly looking at the Angular docs, and checking StackOverflow when I can't figure something out. Also, Firebase is a fantastic resource for learning Angular because they provide a lot of great code snippets and best practices that make it a lot easier to understand the concepts of AngularJS as a whole. 

The parts of AngularJS that are more difficult to understand, in my opinion, are (1) properly structuring states, (2) correctly building and chaining promises to avoid callback soup hell, (3) knowing the difference between factories, services, and providers, and when to apply which. As a CS major, it's pretty easy to "feel" when you're doing something wrong, and then its just a matter of figuring out what to search for on style guides or StackOverflow. 

I approached AngularJS by learning as much documentation as possible. I've memorized the Firebase JS docs at this point, and I've spent a lot of time reading the AngularJS docs. Google has style guides that clarify a lot as well. Also, looking at other people's Angular code as much as possible helps a lot too, but you have to be aware of what others might be doing wrong. 

This is where Firebase comes in clutch -- they are really, really good engineers, and their code is really easy to understand and replicate. If you focus on understanding how to  correctly use Firebase, then you end up learning how to correctly build in AngularJS. 

Here are some resources:
- AngularJS docs: https://docs.angularjs.org/api
- Google Style Guide: https://google-styleguide.googlecode.com/svn/trunk/angularjs-google-style.html
- Firebase Examples: https://www.firebase.com/docs/web/examples.html
